1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,720
So you don't need to memorize hundreds or thousands

2
00:00:02,720 --> 00:00:04,400
of trade setups to be a good trader.

3
00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:07,040
You only need to get good at recognizing a few.

4
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:10,480
In my 25 years of trading and now 15 years of teaching,

5
00:00:10,480 --> 00:00:13,640
including creating 50 plus millionaire students from scratch,

6
00:00:13,640 --> 00:00:15,660
here are the five basic setups

7
00:00:15,660 --> 00:00:17,760
that have made my students and I the most money.

8
00:00:17,760 --> 00:00:19,399
And stay tuned for number five

9
00:00:19,399 --> 00:00:22,679
because this is my favorite setup, especially for beginners.

10
00:00:22,679 --> 00:00:27,039
Setup number one, the multi-day breakout at any time.

11
00:00:27,039 --> 00:00:29,559
So what do I mean by a multi-day breakout?

12
00:00:29,559 --> 00:00:33,960
Here's an example, an STEM was spiking right here

13
00:00:33,960 --> 00:00:36,439
and you can see this, this was in mid July,

14
00:00:36,439 --> 00:00:37,920
we were in Las Vegas.

15
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:41,600
And I love looking at past highs

16
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:44,840
and seeing where that key breakout level is.

17
00:00:44,840 --> 00:00:49,840
And you can see here, clear as day on July 18th,

18
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:54,840
there was a breakout above this former high here in mid June.

19
00:00:54,920 --> 00:00:59,799
And pretty big green candle right at the highs.

20
00:00:59,799 --> 00:01:02,600
And now it's easy to say, yeah, in hindsight,

21
00:01:02,600 --> 00:01:04,799
it spiked up and it was a nice breakout.

22
00:01:04,799 --> 00:01:06,500
But I actually did it in real time.

23
00:01:06,500 --> 00:01:09,519
And a lot of my inner circle students were surprised.

24
00:01:09,519 --> 00:01:11,480
I was sitting right next to Stradi actually.

25
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:13,560
He's my newest millionaire student

26
00:01:13,560 --> 00:01:15,159
as of the time I'm filming this.

27
00:01:15,159 --> 00:01:16,439
And he didn't even understand.

28
00:01:16,439 --> 00:01:17,760
He was like, why are you buying this?

29
00:01:17,760 --> 00:01:20,120
And I'm like, this is an unknown AI play

30
00:01:20,120 --> 00:01:23,000
and it is breaking out today, okay?

31
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:24,480
Sometimes that's all it takes.

32
00:01:25,079 --> 00:01:27,239
I need you to understand that we're looking at charts,

33
00:01:27,239 --> 00:01:29,000
technical analysis matters.

34
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,739
And if you look at these charts and focus on them,

35
00:01:31,739 --> 00:01:35,459
you will see stocks that have hit a very specific price,

36
00:01:35,459 --> 00:01:37,799
two, three, four, five days ago,

37
00:01:37,799 --> 00:01:39,879
two, three, four, five weeks ago.

38
00:01:39,879 --> 00:01:42,680
You're looking for that very specific price

39
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:45,239
and you're looking for a breakout over that price.

40
00:01:45,239 --> 00:01:46,439
Why does it matter?

41
00:01:46,439 --> 00:01:48,439
Because there are so many different traders

42
00:01:48,439 --> 00:01:50,200
who have technical screens

43
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:53,599
and they look for specific breakouts over key levels.

44
00:01:53,599 --> 00:01:55,319
And you want as many traders

45
00:01:55,319 --> 00:01:57,760
looking at one key level as possible.

46
00:01:57,760 --> 00:01:58,599
Why?

47
00:01:58,599 --> 00:02:01,159
Because longs like to buy those breakouts.

48
00:02:01,159 --> 00:02:04,879
It shows that the stock might be in for a bigger run-up.

49
00:02:04,879 --> 00:02:06,599
And you also have short sellers.

50
00:02:06,599 --> 00:02:08,479
Short sellers bet against stocks.

51
00:02:08,479 --> 00:02:11,479
If the stock that they're betting against hits a new high,

52
00:02:11,479 --> 00:02:12,919
they stop out, okay?

53
00:02:12,919 --> 00:02:15,139
That's what responsible short sellers do.

54
00:02:15,139 --> 00:02:17,599
So when you add that key multi-day

55
00:02:17,599 --> 00:02:20,520
or ideally multi-week breakout point,

56
00:02:20,520 --> 00:02:22,900
all the longs are focused on that breakout.

57
00:02:22,900 --> 00:02:24,780
So you get a rush of new buyers

58
00:02:24,780 --> 00:02:27,780
and the shorts are focused on that breakout level

59
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:29,379
and they wanna cover their shares.

60
00:02:29,379 --> 00:02:31,379
When a short seller covers their shares,

61
00:02:31,379 --> 00:02:32,819
they're buying back to cover.

62
00:02:32,819 --> 00:02:34,840
So you have two groups of buyers

63
00:02:34,840 --> 00:02:37,500
at this key specific breakout point.

64
00:02:37,500 --> 00:02:39,340
When you have those two groups,

65
00:02:39,340 --> 00:02:42,699
usually you get a rush and you get a quick breakout,

66
00:02:42,699 --> 00:02:46,099
especially if it's a lower price volatile play

67
00:02:46,099 --> 00:02:48,819
in a hot sector like AI or crypto right now.

68
00:02:48,819 --> 00:02:51,340
And you get that multi-day multi-week breakout.

69
00:02:51,340 --> 00:02:54,099
The stock cannot just break out one or 2%,

70
00:02:54,099 --> 00:02:57,300
but oftentimes that breakout is 10, 20, 30%

71
00:02:57,300 --> 00:02:59,780
within a few minutes or a few hours.

72
00:02:59,780 --> 00:03:01,460
You do have to be careful though,

73
00:03:01,460 --> 00:03:03,180
if you're going for that breakout

74
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:05,460
and for whatever reason it breaks out a little bit

75
00:03:05,460 --> 00:03:07,419
and then it comes smashing back down.

76
00:03:07,419 --> 00:03:08,259
That happens.

77
00:03:08,259 --> 00:03:09,979
There are fake out breakouts.

78
00:03:09,979 --> 00:03:11,620
But in an ideal world,

79
00:03:11,620 --> 00:03:13,819
you buy the multi-day multi-week breakout.

80
00:03:13,819 --> 00:03:16,360
All you have to do is draw a simple line on your chart,

81
00:03:16,360 --> 00:03:17,740
look at the previous high,

82
00:03:17,740 --> 00:03:19,780
and if it breaks it convincingly,

83
00:03:19,780 --> 00:03:22,080
the stock usually rises quite a bit,

84
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:24,439
especially if there's the right news catalyst,

85
00:03:24,439 --> 00:03:25,819
if it's in a hot sector,

86
00:03:25,819 --> 00:03:29,460
if we're in a bull market like we are right now in 2025.

87
00:03:29,460 --> 00:03:33,060
I literally interviewed David Hamlin just a few weeks ago.

88
00:03:33,060 --> 00:03:35,259
He just crossed $10 million in profits.

89
00:03:35,259 --> 00:03:38,300
He made a million dollars on his crypto breakout.

90
00:03:38,300 --> 00:03:40,099
Bitcoin broke out to new highs.

91
00:03:40,099 --> 00:03:42,379
Aaron said, have there been false breakouts

92
00:03:42,379 --> 00:03:44,819
that you've seen recently where you wanted to size in,

93
00:03:44,819 --> 00:03:48,830
but something didn't work?

94
00:03:48,830 --> 00:03:51,430
Stuff has honestly been working pretty well

95
00:03:51,430 --> 00:03:53,629
for the most part just in this current market

96
00:03:53,629 --> 00:03:54,669
because everything's really hot.

97
00:03:54,669 --> 00:03:55,750
It was a trick question.

98
00:03:55,750 --> 00:03:56,949
I know everything's working.

99
00:03:56,949 --> 00:03:57,949
It's great.

100
00:03:57,949 --> 00:04:00,949
Welcome to the bull market, buy those breakouts.

101
00:04:00,949 --> 00:04:03,750
So setup number two are these morning spikers

102
00:04:03,750 --> 00:04:07,750
and lately this is including pre-market starting at 4 a.m.

103
00:04:07,750 --> 00:04:10,310
I know it's not fun to get up at 4 a.m. Eastern.

104
00:04:10,310 --> 00:04:12,550
Congratulations if you're one of my European students,

105
00:04:12,550 --> 00:04:13,830
you live in the right time zone.

106
00:04:13,830 --> 00:04:16,589
But whether it's 4 a.m., whether it's 7 a.m.,

107
00:04:16,589 --> 00:04:18,350
whether it's 9.30 a.m.,

108
00:04:18,350 --> 00:04:21,790
these three key times are when stocks can really spike.

109
00:04:21,790 --> 00:04:23,910
4 a.m. Eastern is when a lot of brokers

110
00:04:23,910 --> 00:04:25,589
like Interactive Brokers open.

111
00:04:25,589 --> 00:04:28,069
7 a.m. Eastern is when retail brokers

112
00:04:28,069 --> 00:04:30,589
like E-Trade or TD Ameritrade open.

113
00:04:30,589 --> 00:04:34,029
9.30 a.m. Eastern is when every broker opens

114
00:04:34,029 --> 00:04:35,709
and that's normal market hours.

115
00:04:35,709 --> 00:04:38,709
But these key levels are when, guess what?

116
00:04:38,709 --> 00:04:41,610
The stock market opens and people can buy stocks.

117
00:04:41,610 --> 00:04:43,870
So I'm looking for stocks with news.

118
00:04:43,870 --> 00:04:45,790
I'm looking for stocks with volume.

119
00:04:45,790 --> 00:04:50,430
I'm trying to buy stocks that are already up 5%, 10%, 20%,

120
00:04:50,430 --> 00:04:53,189
even 50% because in this market,

121
00:04:53,189 --> 00:04:57,310
a stock that's already up gets all these traders interested.

122
00:04:57,310 --> 00:05:00,750
There's all these different chat rooms right now in 2025.

123
00:05:00,750 --> 00:05:02,290
It's a crazy bull market.

124
00:05:02,290 --> 00:05:05,230
So traders are looking for anything that is moving

125
00:05:05,230 --> 00:05:10,230
because a stock that's up 10, 20, 30% can go up 50, 100, 200

126
00:05:10,910 --> 00:05:12,389
with the right news catalyst.

127
00:05:12,389 --> 00:05:14,829
I wouldn't buy a stock without a news catalyst.

128
00:05:14,829 --> 00:05:17,490
There are a lot of morning spikers that just spike

129
00:05:17,490 --> 00:05:19,629
because different chat rooms are buying them.

130
00:05:19,629 --> 00:05:21,189
When the chat room buys them, they go up.

131
00:05:21,189 --> 00:05:23,709
When the chat room sells them, they go down very quickly.

132
00:05:23,709 --> 00:05:24,870
You don't really know.

133
00:05:24,870 --> 00:05:28,310
If there's a news catalyst, if there's enough volume,

134
00:05:28,310 --> 00:05:30,230
if the stock is already spiking a little bit,

135
00:05:30,230 --> 00:05:33,129
and ideally if enough short sellers are lured

136
00:05:33,129 --> 00:05:37,029
into shorting it, you are supposed to buy this stock.

137
00:05:37,029 --> 00:05:40,230
I know it's scary to just buy any stock spiking,

138
00:05:40,230 --> 00:05:42,310
but ideally I like buying a stock

139
00:05:42,310 --> 00:05:45,189
on a 10 or 20% dip off the morning highs.

140
00:05:45,189 --> 00:05:47,350
And then if it breaks through the highs,

141
00:05:47,350 --> 00:05:50,350
it can spike very fast as the shorts cover

142
00:05:50,350 --> 00:05:53,069
as more other traders buy the breakout.

143
00:05:53,069 --> 00:05:55,470
If you're liking this video, make sure you go back

144
00:05:55,470 --> 00:05:58,550
and watch this video about how I consistently find

145
00:05:58,550 --> 00:06:01,589
the best stocks to day trade and subscribe to this channel

146
00:06:01,589 --> 00:06:04,149
so you don't miss any of my upcoming videos

147
00:06:04,149 --> 00:06:06,730
filled with endless trading knowledge and tips

148
00:06:06,730 --> 00:06:08,910
that I've learned the hard way over 25 years.

149
00:06:08,910 --> 00:06:11,750
Setup number three that I love are these afternoon

150
00:06:11,750 --> 00:06:13,750
and after hours breakouts.

151
00:06:13,750 --> 00:06:16,870
This is when there's been a lot of price action

152
00:06:16,870 --> 00:06:20,350
that's happened all day that you can now bounce ideas off of.

153
00:06:20,350 --> 00:06:23,910
And ideally there was a high set at 7 a.m.

154
00:06:23,910 --> 00:06:25,850
or 9 a.m. or 12 p.m.

155
00:06:25,850 --> 00:06:28,750
But there's a distinct high of the day set already

156
00:06:28,750 --> 00:06:31,389
and you're looking for a breakout over that key level

157
00:06:31,389 --> 00:06:33,629
in the afternoon or after hours.

158
00:06:33,629 --> 00:06:36,829
And I actually like afternoon and after hour setups,

159
00:06:36,829 --> 00:06:39,670
especially for beginners because they're not as fast

160
00:06:39,670 --> 00:06:41,949
as morning spikers or pre-market spikers.

161
00:06:41,949 --> 00:06:44,149
In the afternoon, there's a lot of data

162
00:06:44,149 --> 00:06:45,470
from that day already.

163
00:06:45,470 --> 00:06:48,509
So you might not get the same excessive breakouts

164
00:06:48,509 --> 00:06:51,230
or the same excessive runs that you would get

165
00:06:51,230 --> 00:06:53,670
early in the morning, but it's safer.

166
00:06:53,670 --> 00:06:56,110
And oftentimes it's a lot easier for newbies

167
00:06:56,110 --> 00:06:59,149
who are not used to the speed and the volatility

168
00:06:59,149 --> 00:07:03,310
that comes with morning spikers or pre-market spikers.

169
00:07:03,310 --> 00:07:05,949
This is a good example of an afternoon runner.

170
00:07:05,949 --> 00:07:07,149
So this is the daily chart,

171
00:07:07,149 --> 00:07:09,230
but let me just show you the last 10 days.

172
00:07:09,230 --> 00:07:13,129
This doesn't just run all day long.

173
00:07:13,129 --> 00:07:15,829
This actually runs at different times.

174
00:07:15,829 --> 00:07:18,430
So let me show you this one minute chart.

175
00:07:18,430 --> 00:07:21,310
And this one actually tends to do pretty poorly

176
00:07:21,310 --> 00:07:24,509
in the morning, probably just because it's up

177
00:07:24,509 --> 00:07:26,589
for so many days, so many weeks,

178
00:07:26,589 --> 00:07:29,110
and shorts are trying to pound them into the ground.

179
00:07:29,110 --> 00:07:30,829
So if it starts to fade in the morning,

180
00:07:30,829 --> 00:07:33,569
hopefully shorts are trying to push it down

181
00:07:33,569 --> 00:07:36,209
so that it panics by midday and in the afternoon.

182
00:07:36,209 --> 00:07:38,310
But every time it makes a new high,

183
00:07:38,310 --> 00:07:40,949
the shorts give up and they get squeezed

184
00:07:40,949 --> 00:07:44,069
and it oftentimes becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy.

185
00:07:44,069 --> 00:07:46,689
When a few shorts get squeezed, they're scared of new highs,

186
00:07:46,689 --> 00:07:49,189
they create the new highs that they're so scared of.

187
00:07:49,189 --> 00:07:52,689
So as you can see here, this was roughly a week ago

188
00:07:52,689 --> 00:07:56,350
and the stock was in the 14s coming down.

189
00:07:56,350 --> 00:07:58,149
And then it kind of bounces a little bit,

190
00:07:58,149 --> 00:07:59,470
but it doesn't make new highs.

191
00:07:59,470 --> 00:08:03,790
Here you have a little uptrend and right around 1.40 PM

192
00:08:03,790 --> 00:08:06,250
and really specifically 2.20 PM here,

193
00:08:06,250 --> 00:08:08,490
you have a nice run up to new highs.

194
00:08:08,490 --> 00:08:11,050
Again, it starts the next day here,

195
00:08:11,050 --> 00:08:13,089
kind of unconvincing breakout.

196
00:08:13,089 --> 00:08:15,610
I mean, it's still higher than here in the 14s,

197
00:08:15,610 --> 00:08:18,750
it's up to the 15s and 16s, but not much.

198
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:22,329
Again, by the afternoon, when the trend is clear

199
00:08:22,329 --> 00:08:25,199
for the day, that's when it can run.

200
00:08:25,199 --> 00:08:29,360
At the same time too, it's less risky because guess what?

201
00:08:29,360 --> 00:08:32,379
If it fails, if the stock does not break out,

202
00:08:32,379 --> 00:08:34,840
if the stock for whatever reason fails

203
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:37,960
to really explode up in the afternoon or after hours,

204
00:08:37,960 --> 00:08:42,039
you just cut it and the market is a lot less unforgiving

205
00:08:42,039 --> 00:08:42,879
than in the morning.

206
00:08:42,879 --> 00:08:45,080
So if you like slower moving trades,

207
00:08:45,080 --> 00:08:48,000
if you like safer trades, I would focus on the afternoon.

208
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:51,240
Setup number four, I love dip buying morning panics,

209
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:53,200
especially on multi-day runners.

210
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:55,200
You have to think about some of these stocks

211
00:08:55,200 --> 00:08:57,580
that have been spiking for two, three, four, five,

212
00:08:57,580 --> 00:08:59,000
six days in a row.

213
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:00,700
Sometimes people are riding them up.

214
00:09:00,700 --> 00:09:03,039
Congratulations to those people with patience.

215
00:09:03,039 --> 00:09:04,379
I'm not one of them.

216
00:09:04,379 --> 00:09:07,419
Because I'm not one of them, I'm always looking for a deal.

217
00:09:07,419 --> 00:09:09,299
No different than like shoppers are looking

218
00:09:09,299 --> 00:09:10,659
at Black Friday deals.

219
00:09:10,659 --> 00:09:13,980
So too, I'm looking for deals in the stock market.

220
00:09:13,980 --> 00:09:16,019
When a stock has been running for several days,

221
00:09:16,019 --> 00:09:19,500
I'm looking for an opportunity to get in on a dip.

222
00:09:19,500 --> 00:09:21,659
And sometimes this happens very quickly,

223
00:09:21,659 --> 00:09:23,419
especially near the market open,

224
00:09:23,419 --> 00:09:26,059
where longs who have been using stop losses

225
00:09:26,059 --> 00:09:29,899
as they ride a stock higher and higher, they get taken out.

226
00:09:29,899 --> 00:09:32,820
This was a few years ago, ZPAS.

227
00:09:32,820 --> 00:09:34,259
This was a multi-day runner

228
00:09:34,259 --> 00:09:36,620
over the past few days ahead of time.

229
00:09:36,620 --> 00:09:38,940
And you can see here, right near the open,

230
00:09:38,940 --> 00:09:43,340
it tanks from 260 down to the 170s,

231
00:09:43,340 --> 00:09:45,460
and then bounces very quick.

232
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:48,500
So if you're prepared for these big panics,

233
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:50,500
that would be great to dip buy.

234
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:51,980
For example, if a stock, let's say,

235
00:09:51,980 --> 00:09:55,820
has gone from one to six over five days,

236
00:09:55,820 --> 00:09:58,360
and the stock drops in the morning for whatever reason,

237
00:09:58,360 --> 00:10:00,580
due to the market, due to some negative news,

238
00:10:00,580 --> 00:10:02,720
due to just some profit taking,

239
00:10:03,620 --> 00:10:06,519
if it drops from six to five, and $5 is a round number,

240
00:10:06,519 --> 00:10:09,960
so a lot of newbies use stop losses right at round numbers

241
00:10:09,960 --> 00:10:11,559
to try to protect themselves,

242
00:10:11,559 --> 00:10:14,820
if all those stop losses at $5 a share get taken out,

243
00:10:14,820 --> 00:10:18,000
it creates a tsunami of automated sell orders.

244
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:22,039
And a stock might drop from $5 a share down to like 450,

245
00:10:22,039 --> 00:10:25,720
or even $4 a share, within a few seconds or a few minutes.

246
00:10:25,720 --> 00:10:29,320
And that opens the door to a nice, solid opportunity

247
00:10:29,320 --> 00:10:33,200
where the stock, for literally no reason or a small reason,

248
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:36,480
might drop 20, 30, 40% within a few seconds

249
00:10:36,480 --> 00:10:39,000
or a few minutes, and if you're prepared,

250
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,419
you can then utilize your small account to your advantage,

251
00:10:42,419 --> 00:10:46,159
and then you can flip it for a quick 5, 10, 20% bounce

252
00:10:46,159 --> 00:10:47,000
sometimes.

253
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:49,759
It's not as easy as the breakout buys,

254
00:10:49,759 --> 00:10:52,080
and you do have to worry about trying

255
00:10:52,080 --> 00:10:53,679
to catch a falling knife.

256
00:10:53,679 --> 00:10:55,559
There's a saying, if you try to catch a falling knife,

257
00:10:55,559 --> 00:10:57,000
you end up with bloody hands.

258
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:59,159
So sometimes if the stock drops,

259
00:10:59,159 --> 00:11:00,720
and it's not just due to stop losses,

260
00:11:00,720 --> 00:11:03,299
but it's due to actually some big bad news

261
00:11:03,299 --> 00:11:05,639
that you don't know about, the stock can keep dropping.

262
00:11:05,639 --> 00:11:08,659
So it is a little risky to just dip by a panic

263
00:11:08,659 --> 00:11:10,039
without knowing why.

264
00:11:10,039 --> 00:11:14,159
But if you know that there's no specific big bad reason

265
00:11:14,159 --> 00:11:15,159
that the stock is dropping,

266
00:11:15,159 --> 00:11:17,080
and it probably is just stop losses,

267
00:11:17,080 --> 00:11:18,960
you can scalp that quick.

268
00:11:18,960 --> 00:11:21,320
I've done it throughout my career many times,

269
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,340
especially in the past.

270
00:11:22,340 --> 00:11:25,679
In 2025, dip buys haven't worked as great

271
00:11:25,679 --> 00:11:27,039
because a lot of the biggest runners

272
00:11:27,039 --> 00:11:29,740
are just short squeezes, and once the shorts cover,

273
00:11:29,740 --> 00:11:32,460
there's really not that many buyers left.

274
00:11:32,460 --> 00:11:35,039
But at the same time, if there's the right setup,

275
00:11:35,039 --> 00:11:38,600
and specifically, you're watching these multi-day setups,

276
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:39,799
then you have more time.

277
00:11:39,799 --> 00:11:41,480
Because if you're watching a stock spike

278
00:11:41,480 --> 00:11:44,059
two, three, four, five, six, seven days in a row,

279
00:11:44,059 --> 00:11:45,840
you should be watching it every morning

280
00:11:45,840 --> 00:11:48,019
for a potential panic dip buy opportunity.

281
00:11:48,019 --> 00:11:50,460
So knowing the best times to buy and sell,

282
00:11:50,460 --> 00:11:52,460
it's amazing knowing these key setups,

283
00:11:52,460 --> 00:11:55,620
but I really want you to watch this other video that I did

284
00:11:56,559 --> 00:11:58,139
on when to take profits, when to cut losses,

285
00:11:58,139 --> 00:12:00,779
because that really applies to these setups.

286
00:12:00,779 --> 00:12:03,620
Number five, my favorite setup for beginners.

287
00:12:03,620 --> 00:12:04,840
Save the best for last.

288
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:06,480
It's the first green day pattern.

289
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:07,320
Why is it the best?

290
00:12:07,320 --> 00:12:09,019
Because it's the slowest moving.

291
00:12:09,019 --> 00:12:11,320
As a newbie, I know that it's very confusing.

292
00:12:11,320 --> 00:12:13,539
A lot of these plays move very fast.

293
00:12:13,539 --> 00:12:14,940
This is so simple.

294
00:12:14,940 --> 00:12:17,940
It's literally just buying a stock into the close,

295
00:12:17,940 --> 00:12:20,580
whether it's 4 p.m., normal market hours,

296
00:12:20,580 --> 00:12:22,860
or 8 p.m., after hours hours.

297
00:12:22,860 --> 00:12:25,240
But either way, you're buying the stock

298
00:12:25,240 --> 00:12:27,019
on a first green day.

299
00:12:27,019 --> 00:12:27,860
What does that mean?

300
00:12:27,860 --> 00:12:30,720
The candle, if you look in the daily chart, is green,

301
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:34,899
but also you wanna buy a stock that's up 10, 20, 30, 40%

302
00:12:34,899 --> 00:12:35,740
already.

303
00:12:35,740 --> 00:12:37,059
You want the stock in play.

304
00:12:37,059 --> 00:12:39,059
Ideally, you want there to be a catalyst.

305
00:12:39,059 --> 00:12:40,679
I really love the first green day.

306
00:12:40,679 --> 00:12:44,600
This is a beautiful breakout, multi-day, multi-week breakout

307
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:45,799
first green candle.

308
00:12:45,799 --> 00:12:47,419
Look for these big candles

309
00:12:47,419 --> 00:12:49,139
because that's when they can keep going.

310
00:12:49,139 --> 00:12:51,220
LAC, let's go to the daily chart.

311
00:12:51,259 --> 00:12:53,139
You can see here the big gap up.

312
00:12:53,139 --> 00:12:54,539
This was a first green day.

313
00:12:54,539 --> 00:12:57,539
And the first green day leads to a second green day.

314
00:12:57,539 --> 00:13:00,139
So don't be afraid to buy high.

315
00:13:00,139 --> 00:13:01,419
And the first green day pattern

316
00:13:01,419 --> 00:13:03,379
is all about buying this momentum

317
00:13:03,379 --> 00:13:05,740
where there's a little bit of price discovery,

318
00:13:05,740 --> 00:13:07,299
where the company, for whatever reason,

319
00:13:07,299 --> 00:13:08,940
based on the news, based on the chart,

320
00:13:08,940 --> 00:13:10,899
ideally based on the news and the chart,

321
00:13:10,899 --> 00:13:12,220
is getting discovered.

322
00:13:12,220 --> 00:13:13,759
And when it's the first day,

323
00:13:13,759 --> 00:13:16,259
because most people are not focused on small caps

324
00:13:16,259 --> 00:13:19,039
and micro caps, there's a timing inefficiency,

325
00:13:19,039 --> 00:13:20,340
especially over the weekend.

326
00:13:20,340 --> 00:13:24,620
My single best and most winning strategy of all

327
00:13:24,620 --> 00:13:27,580
is buying a stock on a first green day on a Friday

328
00:13:27,580 --> 00:13:29,419
and then selling it on a Monday

329
00:13:29,419 --> 00:13:31,860
as people like to research it over the weekend.

330
00:13:31,860 --> 00:13:35,059
But whether people are seeing the stock on the scans

331
00:13:35,059 --> 00:13:37,879
or researching it over the weekend or just overnight,

332
00:13:37,879 --> 00:13:40,840
no matter what, they're buying it on day two

333
00:13:40,840 --> 00:13:43,659
because it just popped up on their radar.

334
00:13:43,659 --> 00:13:45,740
This is why I love the inefficiency

335
00:13:45,740 --> 00:13:48,240
that exists in the small cap and micro cap market

336
00:13:48,240 --> 00:13:50,100
because there's very little following

337
00:13:50,740 --> 00:13:53,340
and as far as I know, most people are not following

338
00:13:53,340 --> 00:13:56,840
these stocks day to day, let alone minute to minute

339
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:58,019
like I like to do.

340
00:13:58,019 --> 00:14:01,379
So there's a huge opportunity to buy these stocks

341
00:14:01,379 --> 00:14:04,179
on day one, then other traders find it

342
00:14:04,179 --> 00:14:06,220
on day two, day three, day four.

343
00:14:06,220 --> 00:14:07,059
Guess what?

344
00:14:07,059 --> 00:14:11,379
A lot of these stocks that start spiking 50, 100, 200, 500%,

345
00:14:11,379 --> 00:14:13,179
they don't do it all in one day.

346
00:14:13,179 --> 00:14:14,600
It takes several days.

347
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:17,179
So if you're there after the news is already out,

348
00:14:17,179 --> 00:14:19,139
you don't have to guess the news ahead of time

349
00:14:19,139 --> 00:14:22,139
and after the stock has already closed strongly

350
00:14:22,139 --> 00:14:24,860
on a first green day, you can then ride the momentum

351
00:14:24,860 --> 00:14:26,500
into day two, day three, day four.

352
00:14:26,500 --> 00:14:29,019
Jack Kellogg, my top student of all time now

353
00:14:29,019 --> 00:14:32,139
over $22 million, this is his favorite pattern

354
00:14:32,139 --> 00:14:34,139
because he's taking bigger positions now

355
00:14:34,139 --> 00:14:36,860
with his millions of dollars and he's swing trading

356
00:14:36,860 --> 00:14:40,259
and he's profiting by holding a stock that gets discovered

357
00:14:40,259 --> 00:14:43,299
whether it's a small cap stock or a micro cap stock,

358
00:14:43,299 --> 00:14:46,899
AI or crypto, either way, there's some kind of news catalyst

359
00:14:46,899 --> 00:14:48,899
and some kind of technical action

360
00:14:48,899 --> 00:14:50,860
that gets in on everyone's radars

361
00:14:50,860 --> 00:14:53,659
and then the momentum carries over for several days.

362
00:14:53,659 --> 00:14:55,580
Obviously anything can happen overnight

363
00:14:55,580 --> 00:14:57,620
so it doesn't work 100% of the time,

364
00:14:57,620 --> 00:14:59,779
but if you're trying to take the meat of the move

365
00:14:59,779 --> 00:15:01,179
and you're buying the momentum,

366
00:15:01,179 --> 00:15:04,460
look for that first green day on a stock closing strongly

367
00:15:04,460 --> 00:15:07,399
with a news catalyst and sell it day two, day three,

368
00:15:07,399 --> 00:15:08,580
day four, your choice.

369
00:15:08,580 --> 00:15:09,659
I hope this has helped you,

370
00:15:09,659 --> 00:15:11,700
but if you have any questions, comment below,

